issue.title: Refactor Python API docs to better explain IO binding scenarios

labels.name: documentation

repository.name: onnxruntime

issue.body:
**Description**: Improve IO Binding docs

**Motivation and Context**
This [thread](https://www.reddit.com/r/MachineLearning/comments/sobfvm/p_what_we_learned_by_accelerating_by_5x_hugging/) highlighted a usage of IO Binding that we had not documented. This change add documentation for the scenario, as well as restructuring the page for better readability.

Changes staged here: https://natke.github.io/onnxruntime/docs/api/python/api_summary.html

See related issue: #10853

issue.title: Adds missing numpy type when looking for the ort correspondance

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**:
Use of NPY_LONG is ambiguous, it does not have the same meaning on all platforms (see https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/c-api/dtype.html). There were two functions implementing the mapping numpy type --> tensor type. This PR removes the wrong one.

**Motivation and Context**
Fixes issue #10853.

body:
Hi @natke @xadupre , I am also seeing this issue on my end when working on my ONNX exported model, at this specific [line](https://github.com/mstfbl/riiid-acp-pub/blob/2800c89df8b6571f0bd88c63289e224a3dba85a1/05_inference_no_fastai_torch_export.py#L989), with the input being a Numpy `dtype('int64')`/`dtype('long')` matrix. It seems that int64/long Numpy tensors are currently buggy with ORT.

CC @harishsk @harshithapv
Are you able to build ONNX Runtime from source and try with the fix that has just been merged? @mstfbl
